In life. Adult female subglobose, denuded of wax, body appears dark pink to dark purple; legs, eyes and antennae black; dorsal surface thinly covered with white mealy secretion; tufts of wax forming middorsal and marginal longitudinal rows; ventral surface covered with thin white waxy secretion, especially around marsupial opening (adapted from
Cockerell, 1896
).

Description of first-instar nymph (based on 5 paralectotypes of
Icerya ( Crypticerya ) townsendi
)
